lse","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","55672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648918","Department for Education","false","2016-12-07","<p>In the three months leading to August 2016, employment in the Northern Powerhouse was 7.1 million, with 429,000 more people in work than in 2010, and 187,000 jobs created in the past year alone.</p><p> </p><p>The provision of careers education, advice and guidance is crucial in supporting young people to make the right choices about their futures. That is why the Government is investing £90million over the course of this Parliament to improve careers and enterprise provision.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will work with the Northern Powerhouse to ensure that local priorities, including labour market priorities, are fed into the provision of careers advice for young people and adults.</p><p> </p><p>As set out in the Northern Powerhouse Strategy, published at the Autumn Statement this year, the Government will work with local partners in the North on the design of careers and enterprise provision for all ages, including collaboration on the work of the Careers and Enterprise Company and the National Careers Service.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-12-07T15:49:00.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648918/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648918/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-30","Vocational Guidance: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to fulfil the commitment made in the Northern Powerhouse Strategy, published in November 2016, on ensuring that northern labour market priorities inform the provision of careers advice.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","55652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648919","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-08","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy does not collect this data. Ofgem collects and publishes data on those who switch to another tariff with their existing supplier. However, this data does not distinguish between those switching from variable or fixed tariffs.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-08T15:09:21.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648919/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648919/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-30","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many standard variable customers have switched tariff with their own supplier in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","55635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648920","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-08","<p>To improve the Department’s understanding of the impacts of individual electricity generation technologies, Frontier Economics were commissioned to develop a comprehensive framework to define whole system impacts and their components and drivers, which can be applied to a range of electricity generation technologies. The resulting methodology report and its peer reviews will be published in due course.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-08T16:26:25.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648920/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648920/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648920/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648920/answer/previousversion/24574","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-30","Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to page 21 of his Department's report on electricity generation costs, published in November 2016, when his Department plans to publish its findings of the whole system impacts investigation.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","55686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648921","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Government appreciates that the introduction of the National Living Wage (NLW) may mean extra costs for small manufacturing businesses and is committed to ensuring that the National Living Wage works for businesses of all sizes.</p><p>The Government has increased the Employment Allowance by 50% from April 2016, giving employers a £3,000 employer National Insurance Contributions discount. This is estimated to benefit up to 500,000 businesses who, as a result, can employ four people full time on the current NLW and pay no National Insurance Contributions. The increase in the allowance is of greatest benefit to small businesses. We are also extending Small Business Rate Relief meaning 600,000 small businesses will pay no rates at all.</p><p>In addition, the cut in corporation tax from 20% to 17% by the end of the Parliament will benefit over a million firms of all sizes and give the UK the lowest rate of corporation tax in the G20.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-06T15:49:36.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648921/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648921/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-30","Small Businesses: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans his Department has to ensure that small manufacturing businesses have access to grants and other Government schemes to assist them with the proposed increase in the national living wage announced in the Autumn Statement 2016.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","55654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648922","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>There have been a number of recent prosecutions of pyramid selling schemes under the Fraud Act 2006 and the Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading Regulations 2008.</p><p>The Government keeps the law on consumer protection under constant review.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-06T15:48:57.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648922/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648922/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-30","Pyramid Selling: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the regulatory framework for multi-level marketing schemes.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","55715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648923","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>Multi-level marketing schemes where no products are sold can be considered to be pyramid selling which is an unfair practice under Schedule 1 of the Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading Regulations 2008 and may also be considered fraudulent.</p><p>To be legal, multi-level marketing schemes must comply with the Trading Scheme Act 1996 and the Trading Schemes Regulations 1997.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-06T15:48:09.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648923/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648923/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-30","Pyramid Selling: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what regulations govern multi-level marketing schemes in the UK.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","55716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648924","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-08","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-12-08T13:44:15.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648924/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648924/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648924/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-30","Railways: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many rail infrastructure workers in each year since 2010-11 were engaged on (a) zero hours and (b) guaranteed minimum hours contracts.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","55542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648925","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-08","<p>Consideration of the consistency of Network Rail’s workload is a matter for the company to determine, as an arm’s length body from government.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","55538","2016-12-08T12:22:15.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648925/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648925/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-30","Railways: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he has taken to ensure consistency of employment on railway infrastructure in order to guarantee retention of skills.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","55543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648926","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-07","<p>I refer my Right Honourable Friend to my answer of 30 November 2016 to the Hon Member for East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow (Dr Cameron), UIN 54131.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-12-07T15:30:54.533Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648926/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648926/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-30","Transport: Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make an assessment of the UK transport system's progress towards the 2020 target of having 10 per cent of its energy generated by renewables.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","55526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648927","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-05","<p>Interconnectors, as with all electricity infrastructure, may occasionally be unavailable because of the need for repairs and maintenance. However, electricity supplies are secure this winter. In forecasting capacity margins, National Grid allows for unplanned outages – such as this one – in their planning. National Grid has a variety of tools to manage the system and ensure supplies, including 3.5GW of balancing reserve.</p><p>We have not assessed how the damage sustained by the IFA (Interconnexion France-Angleterre) on 20 November will affect the wholesale electricity price, given the various other factors that contribute to wholesale costs, not least the expected direction of flow through IFA this winter.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-05T15:42:21.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648927/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648927/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-30","Electricity Interconnectors: France","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on energy (a) prices and (b) capacity of the damage done to the electricity interconnector between France and the UK during Storm Angus.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","55558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648928","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-05","<p>National Grid and the French transmission system operator are jointly conducting a full investigation into the incident that damaged the interconnector between France and the UK during Storm Angus. Teams on both sides of the Channel are working to restore this interconnector to full availability as soon as possible.</p><p>Interconnector developers employ a variety of tools to reduce the risk of damage to the cable, including thorough sea-bed risk assessments, geotechnical analysis of the sea-bed and a review of shipping routes near the project. Where physically possible, reinforced cables are buried under the sea-bed; where the conditions do not allow for this, the cable is protected by other means, such as rock placement or concrete. Once in service, interconnector cables are regularly surveyed to ensure they remain protected.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-05T15:41:39.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648928/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648928/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-30","Electricity Interconnectors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of whether the incident which damaged the electricity interconnector between France and the UK during Storm Angus has potential safety implications for existing and proposed interconnectors between (a) the UK and other countries and (b) Northern Ireland and Great Britain; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","55559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648929","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Capacity Market enables us to buy energy in advance and is designed to ensure that families and businesses have access to secure, affordable energy supplies they can rely on.</p><p>As the Capacity Mechanism is a series of auctions, prices are subject to strong competition and the costs depend on the auctions’ clearing prices. The two principal auctions held so far have secured capacity needed for 2018/19, and for 2019/20, at costs in those years of around £980m and £830m respectively (2015 values). This equates to gross household bill impacts of around £10 per year, but this figure will be significantly offset when reduced wholesale price spikes are taken into account. Estimates made at the time of the introduction of the Capacity Market in 2014 suggested it would add only £2 net per year to a typical household energy bill on average over the long-term.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-06T10:40:47.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648929/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648929/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648929/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648929/answer/previousversion/24601","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-30","Electricity: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of the Capacity Mechanism on household electricity prices.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","55548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648930","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-08","<p>From 2013–2015, the Government and its agencies (including Innovate UK and the Research Councils) invested on average over £200m per year in support for low carbon innovation. This included support for innovation in the marine sector, including research on tidal power, primarily through the Glasgow-based Offshore Renewable Energy Catapult, Supergen Centre for Marine Energy Research and the Marine Energy Array Demonstrator scheme.</p><p> </p><p>From 2016-2021, the Government has committed to increase the UK’s energy innovation spend, such that by 2021 it will have doubled to over £400m per year. This funding will support innovation across the energy sector in regions across the UK. Round four of Innovate UK’s Energy Catalyst programme has attracted proposals from tidal energy developers and details of other funding opportunities will be set out in due course. Through the new Energy Innovation Board, chaired by Sir Mark Walport, the Department for Business, Energy, and Industrial Strategy will be collaborating with Innovate UK, the Research Councils, and other delivery partners across government, including members of Devolved Administrations, to co-ordinate energy innovation activities.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-08T16:47:15.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648930/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648930/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-30","Tidal Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent steps his Department has taken to support efforts further to research and develop tidal power.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","55531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648931","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-08","<p>From 2013–2015, the Government and its agencies (including Innovate UK and the Research Councils) invested on average over £200m per year in support for low carbon innovation. This included research on wave power, primarily through the Glasgow-based Offshore Renewable Energy Catapult and Supergen Centre for Marine Energy Research.</p><p> </p><p>From 2016-2021, the Government has committed to increase the UK’s energy innovation spend, such that by 2021 it will have doubled to over £400m per year. This funding will support innovation across the energy sector in regions across the UK. The recent launch of phase five of the Energy Entrepreneurs Fund has already attracted interest from wave energy developers and details of other funding opportunities will be set out in due course. Through the new Energy Innovation Board, chaired by Sir Mark Walport, the Department for Business, Energy, and Industrial Strategy will be collaborating with Innovate UK, the Research Councils, and other delivery partners across government, including members of Devolved Administrations, to co-ordinate energy innovation activities.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-08T16:45:18.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648931/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648931/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648931/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-30","Wave Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent steps his Department has taken to support efforts further to research and develop wave power.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","55532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648932","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-08","<p>From 2013–2015, the Government and its agencies (including Innovate UK and the Research Councils) invested on average over £200m per year in support for low carbon innovation. This included support for innovation in offshore wind, including research on floating wind, primarily through the Glasgow-based Offshore Renewable Energy Catapult.</p><p> </p><p>From 2016-2021, the Government has committed to increase the UK’s energy innovation spend, such that by 2021 it will have doubled to over £400m per year. This funding will support innovation across the energy sector in regions across the UK. The recent launch of phase five of the Energy Entrepreneurs Fund has already attracted interest from offshore wind developers and details of other funding opportunities will be set out in due course. Through the new Energy Innovation Board, chaired by Sir Mark Walport, the Department for Business, Energy, and Industrial Strategy will be collaborating with Innovate UK, the Research Councils, and other delivery partners across government, including members of Devolved Administrations, to co-ordinate energy innovation activities.</p><p> </p><p>Following the announcement of the next Contract for Difference auction round, offshore wind projects above 300 MW wishing to enter the auction round must submit a Supply Chain Plan for assessment by the Department. The Government will assess the extent to which plans support Competition, Innovation and Skill in supply chains.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-08T16:51:28.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648932/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648932/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648932/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-30","Wind Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent steps his Department has taken to support efforts further to research and develop (a) offshore wind and (b) floating wind power.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","55533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648933","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-07","<p>The Working Group on Product Recalls and Safety includes representatives from a wide range of experts including the Chief Fire Officers Association, the Association of Chief Trading Standards Officers, Electrical Safety First, the Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents (RoSPA), many of whom represent the interests of individuals and consumers.</p><p>I have met with Which? to talk to them about the Working Group and they have been invited to join the Group.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-07T16:32:28.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648933/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648933/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-30","Product Recalls and Safety Working Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what representations his Department is planning to seek from consumer groups on the working group on product recalls and safety; and what representation consumer groups will have on the membership of that group.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","55610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648934","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-05","<p>As per my answer of 29 November to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-11-24/54761/" target="_blank">54761</a>, the location and provision of its post offices branches is the responsibility of Post Office Limited.</p><p> </p><p>I have asked Paula Vennells, the Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the Hon Member on this matter and provide the information requested. A copy of her reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-05T17:30:06.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648934/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648934/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-30","Post Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 29 November 2016 to Question 54761, on what dates each of the post offices in Bargain Booze shops was opened.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","55589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648935","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-08","<p>Israeli settlements in the Occupied Palestinian Territories report their trade through Israel. It is not possible to disaggregate imports from Israeli settlements from other Israeli imports.</p><p>HMRC figures show the UK imported 340,000 tonnes of goods from Israel in the 12 months ending September 2016. These goods were worth £1 billion.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-12-08T13:49:20.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648935/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648935/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648935/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-30","Imports: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has made of the volume of goods imported from Israeli settlements in the Occupied Palestinian Territories to the UK in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","55735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648936","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-08","<p>My noble Friend the Minister of State for Trade Policy at the Department for International Trade met with the Welsh Government’s Cabinet Secretary for Economy and Infrastructure on 3 November and discussed the Government’s trade priorities. We will continue to engage regularly with all Devolved Administrations on our trade priorities.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-08T12:56:08.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648936/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648936/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-30","Overseas Trade: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what representations he has received from the Welsh Government on World Trade Organisation Schedules of concessions and quotas relating to tariffs and non-tariff barriers after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","55737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648938","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-08","<p>The Department is working closely with the Treasury and other Departments across Whitehall as we prepare our negotiating position. Collectively, we are working to ensure that people and businesses have stability and certainty in the period leading up to our departure from the EU and that we secure a deal in the best interests of the UK.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-12-08T14:59:10.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648938/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648938/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648938/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-11-30","European Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the future use of funding held as part of the UK share in the capital of the European Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","55567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648939","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-08","<p>The implications of exiting the EU for the devolution settlements will require discussion with the devolved administrations. The Prime Minister has made clear her intention to engage with the devolved administrations, and the Joint Ministerial Committee (EU Negotiations) has been established to provide a forum for the discussion of issues stemming from the negotiation process.<br><br></p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-12-08T14:51:05.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648939/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648939/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648939/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-11-30","Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will take steps to ensure that the Northern Ireland Assembly and the other devolved administration have the power to affirm or reject EU legislation governing devolved matters after the Great Repeal Bill becomes law; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","55633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648940","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-08","<p>Hate crime of any kind, directed against any community, race or religion, has absolutely no place in our society. The government is firmly committed to tackling hate crime, which is why we have published a new Hate Crime Action Plan which focuses on reducing hate crime, increasing reporting and improving support for victims. We have also launched a new funding scheme to help protect places of worship.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-12-08T14:52:38.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648940/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648940/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648940/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-11-30","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that racism, hate crime and dog whistle tactics are routinely condemned during the UK's negotiations on leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","55616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649069","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-14","<p>There have been 842 magistrate resignations in England and Wales so far this financial year. Data on numbers of resignations from the magistracy is not routinely published, but is disclosed on request.</p><p>This Government values the judiciary greatly. A strong, independent judiciary is essential for a modern, democratic society and we do not take for granted the central role judges play in upholding the rule of law and delivering justice. Magistrate remains a sought after role and competition for vacancies tends to be strong.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-12-14T17:50:38.53Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649069/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649069/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-30","Magistrates: Resignations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many magistrates have resigned this year; and why this figure has not previously been disclosed.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL3696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649071","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-14","<p>Last month we launched the Prison Safety and Reform White Paper and we are already implementing measures to tackle drugs, drones and phones. This major overhaul of the prison system will include the recruitment of an extra 2,500 frontline officers. Our reforms will empower governors to make the changes they need, ensuring that prisons are places of safety and reform.</p><p>Of course, people will leave the service due to retirement or other reasons, so therefore we will also be recruiting to fill those spaces. We estimate that this will lead to us recruiting 8,000 prison officers in total over the next 2 years. This means that by the end of 2018 the overall frontline workforce will have risen from 19,000 to 21,500.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-12-14T17:51:12.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649071/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649071/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-30","Prison Officers: Recruitment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the announcement by the Justice Secretary on 3 November that 2,500 additional prison officers are to be recruited to address issues including safety, how many officers will need to be recruited to replace existing officers as they leave the service, and over what timescale.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL3697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649072","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-06","<p>The UK supports the goal of eliminating viral hepatitis through multiple channels. Provision of clean water, sanitation and hygiene promotion reduces the risk of transmission of Hepatitis A and E. DFID supports the immunisation of over 300 million children against Hepatitis B through Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance. Support to UNITAID helps to improve access to better diagnostics for Hepatitis C and DFID’s contribution to the Global Fund supports programmes that reduce transmission of both HIV and Hepatitis C.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-12-06T17:07:57.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649072/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649072/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-30","Developing Countries: Hepatitis","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have committed to the World Health Organisation's goal to eliminate viral hepatitis as a public health threat by 2030.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL3698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649073","Department of Health","false","2016-12-12","<p>The number of referrals to Improving Access to Psychological Therapies in each clinical commissioning group (CCG) since 2010 in total, is published and available from the Improving Access to Psychological Therapies dataset held by NHS Digital. Table 1 covers <em>Referrals received, entering treatment, and finishing a course of treatment in the year, 2015-16, counts, by clinical commissioning group</em>. A copy is attached.</p><p>The number of referrals to Improving Access to Psychological Therapies recorded as ended in each CCG, in each year, since 2010 which related to people who were assessed as meeting ‘caseness’ is not available in the format requested. CCGs only existed since 1 April 2013. The number of people who completed treatment who were initially at ‘caseness’ is published, but not the number of those whose treatment was recorded as ended.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-12T12:26:00.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649073/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649073/answer","HL3699 table 1.xls","HL3699 table 1.xls","HL3699 TABLE 1","HL3699 TABLE 1","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649073/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Mental Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many referrals to the Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme were recorded as ended in each clinical commissioning group area in each year since 2010, (1) in total, and (2) which related to people who were assessed as meeting caseness.","false","Biography information for Baroness Burt of Solihull",,"Baroness Burt of Solihull","HL3699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649074","Department of Health","false","2016-12-13","<p>The information is not available in the requested format.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-12-13T16:51:46.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649074/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649074/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Mental Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what were the recorded reasons why referrals to the Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme ended in each clinical commissioning group area in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Baroness Burt of Solihull",,"Baroness Burt of Solihull","HL3700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649075","Department of Health","false","2016-12-13","<p>This data is not available in the format requested.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-12-13T16:51:58.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649075/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649075/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Mental Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, with regard to the Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme, what were the initial average anxiety and depression scores for (1) all referrals that ended which related to people who were assessed, (2) all referrals ended which related to people who entered treatment, and (3) all referred persons completing treatment, in each clinical commissioning group area in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Baroness Burt of Solihull",,"Baroness Burt of Solihull","HL3701"
