"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647739","Department of Health","false","2016-12-02","<p>Individual clinical commissioning groups (CCG) are responsible for commissioning the care that will provide the best possible outcomes for their patients in line with their legal duties and National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidance. As such, it is for Vale of York CCG to make an assessment of what impact on patients its decisions will have.</p><p> </p><p>Vale of York CCG has made clear that every patient’s case will be considered in the light of their own particular circumstances and on the basis of clinical need.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","55449","2016-12-02T09:22:45.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647739/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647739/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-29","Surgery: Vale of York","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has received on the decision by Vale of York Clinical Commissioning Group to place restrictions on routine surgery for patients who smoke or are clinically obese; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","55448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647740","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Government is developing a new tobacco control plan, which will build on previous success and will be published shortly.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-06T12:09:05.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647740/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647740/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-29","Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to publish a new tobacco control plan.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","55414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647741","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Department welcomes the recent research on the potential use of <em>Bdellovibrio bacteriovorus</em> in destroying antibiotic resistant bacteria, since such novel therapies may help to slow the development and spread of antimicrobial resistance.</p><p> </p><p>The research demonstrates an unusual approach to tackling resistant bacteria, but it is too soon to assess the efficacy of this method in human therapeutic use, as it is still at an early stage. Nevertheless, it does offer a new potential mechanism for combatting resistant infections, which would be valuable given the lack of new antibiotics. Depending on how the research progresses, we will consult with our expert advisory scientific committee to assess the application of such research for human therapeutic use.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-06T10:35:26.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647741/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647741/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-29","Antimicrobials: Drug Resistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the efficacy of Bdellovibrio bacteriovorus in tackling anti-microbial resistance.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","55415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647742","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>Central government policy on prompt payments requires the Department pay at least 80% of all undisputed commercial invoices within five days, with the remaining undisputed invoices being paid within 30 days.</p><p> </p><p>The Department publishes quarterly information on prompt payments to our suppliers within five, 10 and 30 days on GOV.UK at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/department-of-health-prompt-payment-of-suppliers-data/department-of-health-prompt-payment-of-suppliers-data-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/department-of-health-prompt-payment-of-suppliers-data/department-of-health-prompt-payment-of-suppliers-data-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>Payments data captured by the Department does not separate the commercial payments into private companies and small/medium enterprises (SMEs) and to satisfy SME suppliers alone would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-06T14:27:42.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647742/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647742/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-29","Department of Health: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of payments by his Department to small businesses are made on time and in accordance with the prompt payment code.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","55433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647743","Department of Health","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Department has not issued guidance to general practitioners on stopping the issuing of repeat prescriptions without an appointment.</p><p> </p><p>When issuing repeat prescriptions or prescribing with repeats, prescribers are expected to make sure that procedures are in place to monitor whether the medicine is still safe and necessary for the patient.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-02T09:21:19.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647743/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647743/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-29","Prescriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has issued guidance to GPs on stopping the issuing of repeat prescriptions without an appointment.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","55384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647744","Department of Health","false","2016-12-02","<p>It will be for NHS England to decide the merits of the option to extend the contract, which commenced in September 2015 and is thus some way away from its end date.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-02T09:24:17.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647744/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647744/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-29","Capita: NHS England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential merits of using the option in Capita's contract with NHS England to extend the term of that contract from seven to 10 years.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","55385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647745","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>Although the Home Office publishes aggregated performance data in the annual report and accounts, it is not possible to extract a figure that shows only the prompt payments to small businesses. Home Office officials cannot identify which suppliers are classed as a small business.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-12-06T16:37:31.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647745/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647745/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-29","Home Office: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of payments by her Department to small businesses are made on time and in accordance with the prompt payment code.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","55434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647746","Home Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>It is accepted that to only include the details of the fathers of the couple and not that of the mothers in a marriage register entry is outdated and that the names of both parents should be included. The Home Office continues to work with all interested parties to consider the most efficient and effective way of achieving this change.</p><p>Any change to the marriage register entry would involve amending computer systems and changes to legislation. We continue to seek suitable legislative opportunities to bring forward reform in this area and a timetable will be made available as soon as an opportunity arises to legislate.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-02T12:05:45.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647746/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647746/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-29","Marriage Certificates: Mothers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 9 February 2016 to Question 25738, what subsequent steps have been taken in preparing a timetable for legislative proposals to amend marriage certificates so that they include the mother's name.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","55490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647747","Home Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>Whilst we can provide data on the current addresses of asylum claimants, data on the place of residence at the time of initial decision could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The latest version of the asylum transparency agenda can be found at: Asylum transparency data: August 2016 - Publications - GOV.UK</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-02T10:27:15.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647747/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647747/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-29","Asylum: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications for asylum seekers housed in (a) Greater London, (b) the London Borough of Newham and (c) East Ham constituency have been refused in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","55442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647748","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The guidance builds on the principles set out by the Home Secretary on 24 October. The criteria are intended to ensure that we are focusing on the most vulnerable children. We will be considering all those aged 12 and under, all children referred to us by the French authorities assessed as being at a high risk of sexual exploitation, and those nationalities most likely to qualify for refugee status in the UK, aged 15 or below. In doing this we are also establishing whether it is in each child’s best interests to come here. Since 10 October, we have transferred over 300 unaccompanied minors to the UK from France and, as the Home Secretary told Parliament on 24 October, we expect several hundred more children to be brought to the UK in the coming days and weeks.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-06T16:42:56.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647748/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647748/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-29","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect on the number of children who can enter the UK of the provisions of her Department's guidance, Implementation of section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 in France.","false","Biography information for Michelle Thomson","Edinburgh West","Michelle  Thomson","55508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647749","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>Immigration remains a reserved matter and we will consider the needs of the UK as a whole.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-06T16:42:31.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647749/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647749/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-29","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of applying different immigration rules to Scotland and other constituent parts of the UK.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","55417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647750","Home Office","false","2016-12-07","<p>The new Government hate crime action plan published on 26 July included extra funding to tackle hate crime.</p><p>This includes £2.4 million over three years to provide protective security measures for places of worship that have been subject to, or are vulnerable to, hate crime and £900,000 over three years for community based projects aimed at tackling hate crime.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-12-07T16:52:16.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647750/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647750/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-29","Hate Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what extra funding her Department plans to provide to reflect recent changes in the level of recorded hate crime.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","55370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647751","Home Office","false","2016-12-05","<p>HM Inspectorate of Constabulary (HMIC) is conducting a rolling programme of unannounced National Child Protection Inspections on all police forces in England and Wales.</p><p>The inspection programme aims to assess how effectively police forces safeguard children at risk, including the investigation of child sexual abuse. To date HMIC has published inspection reports for 13 forces and is conducting post-inspection reviews of forces where failings have been identified to ensure that recommendations are being addressed and performance is improving.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-12-05T17:22:18.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647751/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647751/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-29","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police forces other than the Metropolitan Police (a) have been and (b) are currently being investigated by HM Inspectorate of Constabulary in relation to their handling of child sexual abuse cases.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","55289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647752","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>Immigration remains a reserved matter and we will consider the needs of the UK as a whole.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-06T16:42:04.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647752/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647752/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-29","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of applying different immigration rules to Scotland and other constituent parts of the UK.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","55294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647753","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The UK has a proud history of providing protection to those who need it, in accordance with our international obligations under the 1951 Refugee Convention and the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR).</p><p>All those granted refugee status in the UK are given access to the labour market and benefits, and are encouraged to access organisations that can assist with integration.</p><p>The Home Office provides integration loans, which are designed to help new refugees to integrate into UK society by offering support towards housing costs, employment and training.</p><p>The Government has prioritised supporting refugees in their region of origin and the countries that host them through aid and development funding and is at the forefront of international efforts to end the Syrian crisis.</p><p>We have committed to resettling up to 20,000 individuals under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme and 3,000 individuals under the Vulnerable Children’s Resettlement Scheme over the lifetime of this Parliament.</p><p>In Europe, the UK is a leading Member State contributing both financial and practical support for refugees through the European Asylum Support Office and bilaterally with countries such as France, Greece, and Italy.</p><p>This support includes: resources to assist with processing arrivals; £34 million contribution to Greece’s humanitarian response (enabling provision of essential tents, blankets, and sleeping bags); a £10 million Refugee Children Fund for Europe; £1.5 million for humanitarian and research activities in Italy; and naval support for vessels in distress.</p><p>The Government accepted an amendment during the passage of the Immigration Act 2016 to bring a specified number of unaccompanied refugee children from Europe to the UK.</p><p>Since 10 October, we have transferred over 300 unaccompanied children to the UK from France.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-06T16:44:23.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647753/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647753/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-29","Refugees: Europe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to support refugees (a) in the UK and (b) elsewhere in Europe.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","55295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647755","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Department for Exiting the EU (DExEU) is working closely with all Government departments to ensure that the full range of opportunities are taken and risks mitigated across every area of Government policy.</p><p>A central unit has been established to coordinate EU exit work across the Home Office and act as a central contact for DExEU. Units across the Home Office are also feeding into this work.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-12-06T16:37:46.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647755/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647755/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-29","Home Office: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the implications of the UK leaving the EU on her Departmental responsibilities.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","55296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647756","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-02","<p>The UK has responded quickly to the El Nino related drought in Southern Africa, in fulfilment of our pledge to lead global humanitarian responses and leverage support from others. The UK has provided over £170 million in Southern Africa to meet urgent humanitarian needs, including in Mozambique, Zimbabwe, Malawi, Zambia, Lesotho and Madagascar.</p><p>Combined with the wider economic crisis, El Nino threatens to undermine development gains and stability in Mozambique. In July 2016, Ministers approved the allocation of £25 million to provide assistance to around 250,000 people until the end of March 2017, when the next harvest is expected. UK funding is supporting a market-based approach for food and seed provision to secure better value for money. UK funding is also supporting the treatment of malnutrition and improved access to safe water and sanitation.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-12-02T14:11:10.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647756/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647756/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-29","Mozambique: Droughts and Famine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if her Department will make additional assistance available to Mozambique for famine relief and support in dealing with drought.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","55360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647757","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-02","<p>The UK has responded quickly and generously to the El Nino related drought in southern Africa, in fulfilment of our pledge to lead global humanitarian responses and leverage support from others. DFID has provided £4.68million through UN agencies for the humanitarian response to the impact of El Nino in Madagascar and we continue to monitor the situation closely and will consider further support if the situation deteriorates.</p><p>Existing UK support includes funding for UNICEF and FAO emergency operations for nutrition, water and sanitation. It also includes agricultural and livestock assistance to vulnerable households to reduce their food insecurity and protect their livelihoods.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-12-02T14:12:25.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647757/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647757/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-29","Madagascar: Droughts and Famine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if her Department will make additional assistance available to Madagascar for famine relief and support in dealing with drought.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","55361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647758","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-06","<p>The UK Government is firmly committed to promoting and protecting the right to freedom of religion or belief. The UK raises human rights and the rights of minorities on a regular basis at the highest levels in Pakistan and we ensure our development assistance targets the poor, regardless of race, religion, gender, social background, or nationality. The UK Aid funded AAWAZ (aawaz means “voice” in Urdu) Voice and Accountability Programme supports work to foster tolerance and social cohesion between different religious groups. The UK also supports interfaith dialogue in Pakistan to promote a culture of respect for others’ religion or belief.</p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-12-06T15:07:40.663Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647758/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647758/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-29","Pakistan: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what role Government aid plays in assisting the government of Pakistan fulfil its duties under Article 18 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","55331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647759","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-06","<p>The UK Government raises human rights issues and the rights of minorities on a regular basis at the highest levels in Pakistan and we ensure our development assistance targets the poor, regardless of race, religion, gender, social background, or nationality. One of the four principles set out in the UK-Pakistan Partnership Principles Assessment is a commitment by Pakistan to respect human rights and the UK uses this engagement to advocate for enhanced legal protections for minorities in line with Pakistan’s constitution and its international obligations. The Partnership Principles Assessment provides the basis for regular bilateral assistance talks between the UK and Pakistan.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-12-06T15:08:24.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647759/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647759/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-29","Pakistan: Minority Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what role Government aid plays in helping the government of Pakistan strengthen legal protections for minorities in that country.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","55332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647760","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-06","<p>DFID provides funding to the provincial governments of Punjab and Khyber Pakhtunkhwa to help improve educational standards. Our investments help raise standards by increasing teacher and student attendance, improving school facilities, and improving children’s learning outcomes. In Punjab and Khyber Pakhtunkhwa DFID is also supporting government to revise textbooks and replace any content that promotes prejudice and discrimination against religious or other minorities.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-12-06T15:15:48.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647760/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647760/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-29","Pakistan: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what funding the Government provides to the government of Pakistan to help improve educational standards in that country; and whether any such funding is provided to assist in ensuring positive portrayal of minority groups in school curricula.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","55333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647761","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-06","<p>Central Government Departments aim to pay 80% of undisputed and valid invoices within 5 days, with the remainder paid within 30 days.</p><p>In 2015-16 the Department for International Development paid 81.01% of such invoices within 5 days, and 99.44% within 30 days.</p><p>We have published our overall payment performance data at www.gov.uk/government/publications/dfid-payment-performance-2015/dfid-payment-performance-2015-quarterly</p><p>To support prompt payment further, since June 2015 all central Government departments have been required to accept unstructured e-invoices - invoices which can be sent in by email. We are also working towards greater use of structured e-invoices - these are invoices that can be processed automatically thereby reducing payment times and errors.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-12-06T15:20:11.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647761/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647761/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-29","Department for International Development: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of payments by her Department to small businesses are made on time and in accordance with the prompt payment code.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","55435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647762","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-12","<p>This information is publically available on gov.uk.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-12-12T18:56:14.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647762/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647762/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-29","Ministry of Justice: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of payments by her Department to small businesses are made on time and in accordance with the prompt payment code.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","55437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647763","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-07","<p>Sentencing of those found guilty of a criminal offence is a matter for the courts. Magistrates’ courts use sentencing guidelines published by the Sentencing Council to assist them when deciding the appropriate penalty for a particular offence. The Sentencing Council is currently undertaking a review of the guidelines.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","55404","2016-12-07T12:45:22.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647763/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647763/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-29","Animal Welfare: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether she plans to review the sentencing available for offences committed under the Animal Welfare Act 2006.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","55402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647764","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-07","<p>The maximum penalty for an attack by a person on an assistance dog is 6 months’ imprisonment or an unlimited fine or both.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-07T11:09:01.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647764/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647764/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-29","Assistance Animals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the maximum permitted penalty is for an attack by a person on an assistance dog in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","55397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647765","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-12","<p>The Government published in July 2016 “Story of the Prison Population 1993 – 2016”. This is available on gov.uk.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-12T19:23:23.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647765/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647765/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-29","Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment her Department has made of causes of the increase in the prison population since 2004.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","55393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647766","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-16","<p>The Government is committed to making prisons safe. Reducing self-inflicted deaths is a key priority for the Government.</p><p>As part of this, providing the right intervention and treatment is vital to improving the outcomes for people who are suffering or otherwise vulnerable. All prisons have established procedures in place to identify, manage and support people with mental health issues or at risk of suicide or self-harm.</p><p>But we recognise that more can be done. That is why we have invested in specialist mental health training for prison officers, allocated more funding for prison safety and have launched a suicide and self-harm reduction project to address the increase in self-inflicted deaths and self-harm in our prisons.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-16T18:19:37.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647766/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647766/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-29","Prisoners: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment her Department has made of implications for its policies of the findings of the report of the Howard League, Preventing prison suicide, published on 28 November 2016.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","55394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647767","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Government keeps maximum penalties under review.</p><p> </p><p>Details of all ministerial meetings are published in the transparency returns on gov.uk.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-02-03T14:37:46.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647767/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647767/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-29","Animal Welfare: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions Ministers of her Department have had with their counterparts in the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs on the maximum sentence available to the courts for offences under the Animal Welfare Act 2006.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","55403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647768","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-07","<p>Sentencing of those found guilty of a criminal offence is a matter for the courts. Magistrates’ courts use sentencing guidelines published by the Sentencing Council to assist them when deciding the appropriate penalty for a particular offence. The Sentencing Council is currently undertaking a review of the guidelines.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","55402","2016-12-07T12:45:22.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647768/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647768/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-29","Animal Welfare: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when the sentencing available for offences committed under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 was last reviewed.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","55404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647769","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-07","<p>The Government is aware of research that suggests there may be links between trends in different criminal offences such as offences against animals and offences against people, such as the recent research by Malcolm Plant, et al at Teeside University.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","55406","2016-12-07T17:54:32.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647769/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647769/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-29","Animal Welfare: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department has made an assessment of whether there is a link between trends in the level of offences committed under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 and trends in the level of offences of domestic violence in the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","55405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647770","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-07","<p>The Government is aware of research that suggests there may be links between trends in different criminal offences such as offences against animals and offences against people, such as the recent research by Malcolm Plant, et al at Teeside University.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","55405","2016-12-07T17:54:32.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647770/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647770/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-29","Animal Welfare and Hate Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department has made an assessment of whether there is a link between trends in the level of offences committed under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 and trends in the level of aggravated offences against the person in the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","55406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647771","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-20","<p>The reoffending rate for those who committed an offence under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 was on average just over one percent over the last eight years.</p><p>Data on reoffending rates for people convicted of offences under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 is available up to 2014, with a one year follow-up period. Data for 2015 and 2016 will be available in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-20T18:02:23.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647771/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647771/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-29","Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment her Department has made of trends in the level of the recidivism rate of persons who have committed offences under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 in the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","55407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647772","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-07","<p>We will publish the conclusions of our review of Employment Tribunal fees in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-07T17:24:23.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647772/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647772/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-29","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when her Department expects to complete its review into employment tribunal fees.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","55419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647773","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-12","<p>The Justice Secretary announced major reforms to the prison system in the Prison Safety and White Paper published on 3 November, to cut reoffending and help reduce crime.</p><p> </p><p>As announced at Autumn Statement last month, £100 million annually will be allocated to the Ministry of Justice to implement measures to improve safety in prisons and wider reforms to the whole criminal justice system. We will be investing more than £100 million to recruit, train and pay for an additional 2,500 prison officers, helping us to implement the new dedicated prison officer role.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-12T19:21:04.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647773/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647773/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-29","Prisons: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to paragraph 5.17 of the Autumn Statement 2016, how much of the £500 million of extra funding to enable the recruitment of 2,500 extra prison officers and wider reforms will be spent on (a) recruitment costs, (b) salaries, (c) pensions and (d) wider reforms.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","55487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647774","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-16","<p>The Justice Secretary announced major reforms to the prison system in the Prison Safety and Reform White Paper published on 3 November, to cut reoffending and help reduce crime.</p><p>As part of these reforms, we are going to empower governors, giving them the freedom to drive forward reform. That is why from April 2017, we are giving governors the power and budget to determine how their prisons are run. This includes governors having the authority to do their own workforce planning, decide what staffing structures best meets their local needs and deciding how to deploy extra staff in prisons.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-16T18:11:58.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647774/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647774/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-29","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to paragraph 5.17 of the Autumn Statement 2016, how many of the additional prison staff paid for by the £500 million of extra funding to enable the recruitment of 2,500 extra prison officers and wider reforms will be (a) Band 3 to 5 Officers, (b) Operational Support Grade officers and (c) other grades.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","55488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647775","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-07","<p>This information, including an estimation of the number of mentors that are ex-offenders, could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-07T17:15:02.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647775/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647775/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647775/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-29","Prisoners: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate she has made of the number of former prisoners who are currently involved in prisoner mentoring.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","55326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647776","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-07","<p>Data on the number of prisoners released on temporary license is published quarterly, and data for each year going back to 2002 is published on gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p>We know that three of the most powerful factors helping to keep ex-offenders from re-offending are a good job, strong family ties and a stable place to live - ROTL makes all of them easier to achieve. Public protection is our top priority and we have no intention of changing the full risk-assessment offenders on ROTL must undergo and any non-compliance will be dealt with robustly.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-07T17:18:51.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647776/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647776/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647776/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-29","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners have been released on temporary licence in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","55327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647777","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Government is committed to making sure that sentencing for those who kill or cause serious injury on the roads is proportionate within the context of our wider sentencing framework.</p><p>We published the consultation on driving offences and penalties on 5 December.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-20T17:59:27.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647777/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647777/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-29","Dangerous Driving: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, on what date she plans to launch her Department's consultation on sentencing for dangerous driving.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","55348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647778","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-20","<p>We want our prisons to be places where staff and prisoners alike feel safe and secure. The introduction of new ways of working to support prisoners to reform will achieve this while also increasing frontline staff numbers.</p><p>Prison governors will be empowered to determine the precise grade mix and deployment of staff into their establishment to meet the individual needs of their specific prisoner population, in line with set minimum service requirements which are aligned to the NOMS Offender Management model. Staff numbers will vary across establishments, dependant on prisoner population and type of prison.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-20T18:00:46.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647778/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647778/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-29","Hull Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many of the additional 2,500 prison officers the Government plans to recruit will be employed at HM Prison Hull.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","55284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647779","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>Staffing levels within the Electoral Office are a matter for the Chief Electoral Officer.</p><p>However, my officials and I have regular discussions with the Chief Electoral Officer, and I am aware of the Voluntary Exit Scheme that is currently underway.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-12-06T12:22:12.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647779/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647779/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-11-29","Chief Electoral Officer for Northern Ireland: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent discussions he has had with the Office of the Chief Electoral Officer on staffing levels in electoral offices in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","55368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647780","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>Since the publication of the Consultation on the Future Delivery of Electoral Services was published, I have met a range of stakeholders across Northern Ireland to discuss the issues raised, including MPs, district councils, trade union representatives and those involved in the administration of elections<strong>. </strong></p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-12-06T12:23:12.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647780/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647780/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-11-29","Chief Electoral Officer for Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what representations he has received on the reorganisation of electoral offices in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","55367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647781","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-01-06","<p>The Chief Constable and I meet regularly, along with the Justice Minister, to discuss national security in Northern Ireland.</p><p>PSNI do not publish response time statistics broken down by incident type, however overall in the 2016/17 year to date (1 April – 30 November 2016), PSNI responded to 71% of emergency calls within 20 minutes.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-01-06T12:09:20.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647781/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647781/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-11-29","Police: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent discussions he has had with the Chief Constable on the Police Service of Northern Ireland response times to national security incidents.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","55427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647782","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-05","<p>The overriding procurement policy requirement is that all public procurement must be based on value for money, defined as ‘the best mix of quality and effectiveness for the least outlay over the period of use of the goods or services bought’. This should be achieved through competition, unless there are compelling reasons to the contrary.</p><p>Public sector procurement is subject to a legal framework that encourages free and open competition and value for money, in line with internationally and nationally agreed obligations and regulations. As part of its strategy, the government aligns procurement policies with this legal framework, as well as with its wider policy objectives:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/public-sector-procurement-policy" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/public-sector-procurement-policy</a></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-12-05T09:54:30.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647782/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647782/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-29","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what procurement policies are in place when issuing government contracts.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","55411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647783","Women and Equalities","false","2016-12-02","<p>I have read the letter from the Equalities and Human Rights Commission. I would like to take this opportunity to reassure the honourable member that Government always seeks to engage people in a responsible and considered way.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-12-02T10:12:18.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647783/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647783/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-11-29","Equality and Human Rights Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what assessment she has made of the implications for Government policy of the statement from the Equalities and Human Rights Commission on engaging people on contentious issues in a responsible and considered way.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","55392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647784","Scotland Office","false","2016-12-05","<p>The Scottish Government is responsible for rail services and infrastructure investment in Scotland. The further devolution of rail powers was not a recommendation of the cross-party Smith Commission agreement.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government is committed to working closely with the Scottish Government to provide a better railway for passengers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","55464","2016-12-05T12:49:59.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647784/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647784/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-11-29","Railways: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether the Government plans to devolve full rail powers to the Scottish Government.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","55457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647785","Scotland Office","false","2016-12-05","<p>The Scottish Government is responsible for rail services and infrastructure investment in Scotland. The further devolution of rail powers was not a recommendation of the cross-party Smith Commission agreement.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government is committed to working closely with the Scottish Government to provide a better railway for passengers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","55457","2016-12-05T12:49:59.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647785/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647785/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-11-29","Railways: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what discussions he has had with the Department for Transport on devolving full rail powers to the Scottish Government.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","55464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647786","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-07","<p>The Scottish Ministers already have substantial devolved powers in relation to the railways in Scotland. These have recently been supplemented through the Government’s delivery of the recommendations of the cross-party Smith Commission in full. We have no plans to go beyond this.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-12-07T13:10:46.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647786/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647786/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-29","Railways: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of devolving full rail powers to the Scottish Government.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","55465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647787","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-07","<p>Central Government Departments aim to pay 80% of undisputed and valid invoices within 5 days, with the remainder paid within 30 days.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015-16 the Department for Transport paid 93.9% of such invoices within 5 days, and 99.3% within 30 days.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has published its overall payment performance data at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/565053/dft-prompt-payment-data-2016.csv/preview" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/565053/dft-prompt-payment-data-2016.csv/preview</a></p><p> </p><p>To support prompt payment further, since June 2015 all central Government departments have been required to accept unstructured e-invoices - invoices which can be sent in by email. We are also working towards greater use of structured e-invoices - these are invoices that can be processed automatically thereby reducing payment times and errors.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-12-07T15:22:41.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647787/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647787/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-29","Department for Transport: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of payments by his Department to small businesses are made on time and in accordance with the prompt payment code.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","55438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647788","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-07","<p>Whilst Heathrow is operating at capacity today, the Airports Commission recognised that there is still spare capacity in the South East. The Government will be progressing work on a new Aviation Strategy which will consider how we can make best use of existing capacity.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-12-07T15:19:19.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647788/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647788/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-29","Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how his Department plans to meet growth in aviation passenger demand before the completion of a new runway in the South East.","false","Biography information for Robert Neill","Bromley and Chislehurst","Robert Neill","55501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647790","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-07","<p>HS2 Ltd will take the noise evidence provided by RPS Planning and Development into account in the on-going discussions regarding the effects of noise from HS2 on the Bodymoor Heath training ground.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-12-07T09:27:17.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647790/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647790/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-29","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to ensure that HS2 Ltd takes account of the report by RPS Planning and Development, entitled Acoustics assessment of the effects of HS2, rebuttal evidence, published on 24 November 2016, in any discussions on compensation that it has with Aston Villa Football Club relating to the effect of noise from High Speed 2 on that club's Bodymoor Heath training ground.","false","Biography information for Mr Khalid Mahmood","Birmingham, Perry Barr","Mr Khalid Mahmood","55420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647791","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Department for Transport does not hold data on the amount of carbon dioxide emitted from ships transporting coal from Colombia to the UK.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-12-02T12:17:13.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647791/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647791/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-29","Shipping: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department holds data on the amount of carbon dioxide emitted from ships transporting coal from Colombia to the UK for the last 10 years up to the latest year for which data is available; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","55369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647792","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-05","<p>The table below provides a) the number of collisions of all types recorded by Highways England/Highways Agency, and b) the number of personal-injury collision reported to the police, which occurred on the A282 for the time periods requested.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Period</p></td><td><p>a) All collisions recorded by Highways England/Highways Agency</p></td><td><p>b) Personal-injury accidents which were reported to the police</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sept 2010 to August 2011</p></td><td><p>74</p></td><td><p>76</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sept 2011 to August 2012</p></td><td><p>79</p></td><td><p>51</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sept 2012 to August 2013</p></td><td><p>143</p></td><td><p>71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sept 2013 to August 2014</p></td><td><p>318</p></td><td><p>64</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sept 2014 to August 2015</p></td><td><p>675</p></td><td><p>64</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The figures in a) are all incidents described as a “road traffic collision – no injury” or “road traffic collision injury / fatality” but have not been verified. Prior to 2014, incident data was recorded manually in paper format and was completed by staff with multiple responsibilities, so all incidents may not have been recorded.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","55363 ; 55364 ; 55365 ; 55366","2016-12-05T15:36:05.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647792/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647792/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-29","A282","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many vehicle accidents on the A282 were registered by Highways England between 1 September 2014 and 31 August 2015.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","55362"
